  "issue_title": "feature: add focus_input tool",
  "issue_body": "Parent: #75\n\n## Problem\n\n`type_text` currently depends on whichever field is already focused. That is unreliable for forms, search boxes, and settings screens where the intended field is visible but not focused.\n\n## Proposed behavior\n\nAdd a `focus_input` Android tool that focuses a resolved editable target without typing text.\n\nExpected arguments should support the Milestone 4 selector model, such as:\n\n- `text`\n- `node_id`\n- `bounds`\n- `view_id`\n\nThe tool should use the target resolver and only focus editable/input nodes.\n\n## User workflow\n\nA user or local agent can first focus a named input field, then call `type_text` with confidence that text will go to the intended place.\n\n## Local-first impact\n\nThis strengthens deterministic local form control without needing a cloud model.\n\n## Safety and security considerations\n\nFocusing is lower risk than typing, but it can still prepare a sensitive workflow. The action should remain logged and should not bypass policy for the later text entry.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Add `focus_input` to the Android tool catalog.\n- [ ] Resolve target through the Milestone 4 selector/resolver path.\n- [ ] Reject non-editable targets with a clear error.\n- [ ] Preserve policy, approval, and log behavior.\n- [ ] Add unit tests for successful focus, missing target, non-input target, and ambiguous target.\n\n## Alternatives considered\n\nOnly add target handling inside `type_text`. That is still useful, but a separate focus primitive gives the agent a safer, inspectable step for multi-action form workflows.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-27T14:42:17.000Z",
